THE OPERATIONAL AMPLIFIER ^AGcQO4YR

The integrated circuit OP AMP is the premier linear active device
in present-day analog circuit applications. The device itself is a 
complex array of transistors, resistors and diodes, and capacitors,
all fabricated and interconnected on a tiny silicon chip. In spite of 
its complexity, the device can be modeled by rather simple i-v char-
teristics. We do not need to concern ourselves with what is going
on inside the package; rather, we treat the OP AMP using a behav-
ioural model that constraints the voltages and currents at the 
external terminals of the device. ^jDlimz3X

OP AMP NOTATION ^vP8qJdjd

Certain matters of notation and nomenclature must be discussed 
before developing a circuit model for the OP AMP. The OP AMP is a 
five terminal device, as shown in fig 1. The "+" and "-" symbols identify
the input terminals and are a short hand notation for the noninverting
and inverting input terminals respectively. The other terminals are the 
output and the positive and negative supply voltages usually labeled 
+Vcc and -Vcc. While some OP AMPs have more than five terminals,
these five are always present and are the only ones we will use in this
text. fig 2 shows a complete set of voltage and current variables for
the OP AMP. All voltages are defined with respect to a common refer-
ence node, usually ground. Voltage variables vp, vn and vo are defined
by writing the voltage symbol beside the corresponding terminal. ^yVecydFz

The dominant feature of the OP AMP is the transfer characteristics as
shown in fig 3. The characteristics provides the relationship between the
NONINVERTING INPUT Vp, the INVERTING INPUT Vn, and the OUTPUT
VOLTAGE Vo. The transfer characteristics is divided into three regions or
modes called +SATURATION, -SATURATION, and LINEAR. In the linear 
region, the OP AMP is a differential amplifier because the output is propo-
rtional to the difference between the two inputs. The slope of the line in
the linear region is called the voltage gain. In this linear region, the output
voltage relation is: ^CEz6Teio

The voltage gain of an OP AMP is very large, usually greater than     . As
long as the net input(Vp - Vn) is very small, the output will be proportional to 
the input. However, when A|Vp - Vn| > Vcc, the OP amp is saturated and the
output voltage is limited by the supply voltages.

    The OP AMP has three modes of operatoins:
1.  +Saturation mode when A(Vp - Vn) > Vcc and Vo = +Vcc.
2.  -Saturation mode when A(Vp - Vn) < -Vcc and Vo = -Vcc.
3.  Linear mode when A|vp - Vn| < Vcc and Vo = A(Vp - Vn).


    Usually we analyze and design OP AMP circuits using the model for the linear
mode. When the operating mode is not given, we use a self-consistent approach.
That is, we assume that the OP AMP is in the linear mode and then Calculate the
output voltage Vo. If it turns out that -Vcc < Vo < +Vcc, when the assumption is
correct and the OP AMP is indeed in the linear mode. If Vo < -Vcc, then the
assumption is wrong and the OP AMP is in the -saturation mode with Vo = -Vcc.
If Vo > +Vcc, then the assumption is wrong and the OP AMP is in the +saturation
mode with Vo = +Vcc. ^SKKVsUb2

The preceding analysis illustrates a general strategy for analyzing OP AMP circuits. We use 
normal circuit analysis methods to express the OP AMP input voltages vp and vn in terms of circ-
uit parameters. We then use the ideal OP AMP constraints vp = vn to solve for the overall circu-
it input-output relationship
    
    The circuit in fig 5 is called a noninverting amplifier. The input-output relationship is of the 
form vo = Kvs, which reminds us that the circuit is linear. Fig 5b shows the functional block for 
this circuit, where the proportionality constant k is:




In an OP AMP circuit the proportionality constant K is sometimes called the closed loop gain, 
because it defines the input-output relationship when the feedback loop is connected (closed).

    When discussing OP AMP circuits, it is necessary to distinguish between two types of gains.
The first is the larger, OPEN-LOOP voltage gain provided by the OP AMP device itself. The 
second is the closed-loop voltage gain of the OP AMP circuit with a negative feedback path.
NOTE: that equation vi indicates that the circuit gain is determined by the resistors in the 
feedback path, not by the value of the OP AMP gain. In effect, feedback converts the OP AMP's
very large but variable gain into a much smaller but well defined gain.

Let us find the output voltage, the output current, the voltage gain, the output power and the
power gain.

and an output source load. the gain of the OP AMP circuit is found using equation vi as:

We calculate the output current using Ohm's law as follows:




The output power is simply po = vo * io = 5 * 500^-6 = 2.5mW. It does not make sense to talk

REMARK: The problem of choosing resistance values in OP AMP circuit design problems deserves some
discussion. Although values of resistances form a few ohms to several hundred mega ohms are comm-
ercially available, we generally limit ourselves to the range from about 1k to perhaps 10M. The lower 
limit of 1k is imposed in part because of power dissipation in the resistors. Typically, we use resistors
with 1/4w power ratings or less. The maximum voltage in OP AMP circuits is often around 15V. The
smallest 1/4w resistance we can use is Rmin >= (15)^2/0.25 = 900 ohms, or about 1K. The upper
bound of 1M comes about because surface leakages makes it difficult to maintain tolerance in a
high-value resistor. High-value resistors are also noisy, which leads to problems when they are connec-
ted in the feedback path. The 1k to 1M range should be used as a guideline, not an inviolate deisgn
rule. Actual design choices are influenced by system-specific factors and changes in technology. ^P9nWQS3l

OP AMP CIRCUIT ANALYSIS ^WtmmKThu

OP AMP circuit analysis takes advantage of OP AMP building blocks that are connected in cascade
(similar to series) to perform signal analysis functions that are too complex for any one building block
alone. This approach greatly simplifies the analysis and design of these type of circuits. The reason 
this works is that OP AMP building blocks, as we saw, have very low output resistance enabling other
circuits to be connected to their outputs without altering the function of either building block. In some
cases, a passive circuit's signal processing function can be unintentionally altered by connecting that
circuit to another. When this effect occurs, the circuit is said to be "LOADED", and the effect needs
to be considered. Some OP AMP building blocks, such as the noninverter just studied, also have very
high input resistances. This feature enables them to be connected to the output of circuits that are
sensitive to loading, such as voltage dividers, without affecting their signal processing function. In this
section, we introduce four more building blocks to complement the noninverter just studied, These are the
voltage follower, the inverting amplifier, the summer and the subractor. The key to using the building
block approach is to recognize the feedback pattern and to isolate the basic circuit as a building block.
The first example illustrates this process.

THE VOLTAGE FOLLOWER ^lo8zz3EF

FIG 8: a source-load interface with voltage follower.
        b interface without the voltage follower ^zCPzV03S

The OP AMP in fig 8 is connected as a voltage follower or buffer. In this case, the feedback path is a
direct connection from the output to the inverting input. The feedback connection forces the condition 
vn = vo. The input current ip = 0, so there is no voltage across the source resistance Rs. Applying KVL,
we have the input condition vp = vs. The ideal OP AMP model requires vp = vn, so we conclude that 
vo = vs. By inspection, the closed-loop gain is K = 1. Since the output exactly equals, we say that the 
output follows the input (hence the name voltage follower). 
    The voltage follower is used in interface circuits because it isolates the source from the load. Notice
that the input output relationship vo = vs does not depend on the source or load resistance. When the
source is connected directly to the load, as in figure 8b, the voltage delivered to the load depends on Rs
and RL. The source and load interaction limits the signals that can be transferred across the interface.
When the voltage follower is inserted between the source and load, the signal levels are limited by the 
capacity of the OP AMP. By Ohm's law, the current delivered to the load is io = vo/RL. But since vo = vs
the output current can be written in the form io = vs/RL.
Applying KCL at the reference node, we discover an apparent dilemma:
                                            ip = io
For the ideal model ip = 0, but the preceding equations say that io cannot be zero unless vs is zero. It
appears that KCL is violated. 
    The dilemma is resolved by noting that the circuit diagram does not include the supply terminals. The
output current comes from the power supply, not from the input. this dilemma only arises at the reference
node (the ground terminal). In OPAMP circuits, as in all circuits, KCL must be satisfied. However, we must
be alert to the fact that a KCL equation at the reference node could yield misleading results because
the power supply terminals are not usually included in circuit diagrams. ^t2cVLmUN

NODE VOLTAGE ANALYSIS WITH OP AMPS ^KunBK043

There are many useful OP AMP circuits that are not simply interconnections of basic
building blocks. In such cases we use a modified form of node-voltage analysis that
is based on the OP AMP connections shown below. The overall circuit contains N 
nodes, including the three associated with the OP AMP. Normally the objective is to 
find the OP AMP output voltage vo relative to the reference node (ground). We
assign node voltage variables at the OP AMP output. However, an ideal OP AMP 
acts like a dependent voltage source connected between the output terminal and
ground. As a result, the OP AMP output voltage is determined by the other node
voltages, and so we do not need to write a node equation at the OP AMP ouput
node.
    We formulate node equations at the other N-2 nonreference nodes in the usual
way. Since there are N-1 node voltages, we seem to have unknowns than the equati-
ns. However, the OP AMP forces the condition vp = vn. This eliminates one unknown
node voltage since these two nodes are forced to have identical voltages. Finally,
remember that the ideal OP AMP draws no current at its inputs (ip=in=0), so these
currents can be ignored when formulating node equations.
    The following steps outline an approach to the formulation of node equations
for OP AMP circuits:

STEP 1:  Identify a node voltage at all nonreference nodes, including OP AMP outp-
        uts, but do not formulate node equations at the OP AMP output nodes.
STEP 2: Formulate node equations at the remaining nonreference nodes and then
        use the ideal OP AMP voltage constraints vp=vn to reduce the number of
        unknowns. ^cKDeVOuG

Before getting into the details, let us take a look at the figures given below. In
figure(a), the voltage at VB = VA, this is because there is a short circuit between

When complex networks are put into the feedback, the circuits get harder to analyze
because the simple gain equations cannot be used. The usual technique is to write and
node or loop equations. There is only one input voltage, so superposition is not of any
use. but Thevenin's theorem can be used as is shown in the sample problem below.

Sometimes it is desirable to have a low resistance path to ground in the feedback loop.
Standard inverting op amps can not do this when the driving circuit sets the input resistor
value, and the gain specification sets the feedback resistor value. Inserting a T network
in the feedback loop, yields a degree of freedom that enables both specification to be met
with a low dc resistance path in the feedback loop.

SINGLE-SUPPLY OP AP DESIGN TECHNIQUES ^5d24T0Et

We have previously assumed that all op amps were powered from dual or split supplies and
this is not the case in today's world of portable, battery-powered equipment. When opamps
are powered from dual supplies, the supplies are normally equal in magnitude, opposing in 
polarities and the center tap of the supplies is connected to ground. Any input sources
connected to ground are automatically referenced to the center of the supply voltage, so
the output voltage is automatically referenced to ground.









                            SPLIT-SUPPLY OP AMP CIRCUIT

Single-supply systems do not have the convenient ground reference that dual-supply systems
have, thus biasing must be employed to ensure that the output voltage swings between the
correct voltages. Input sources connected to ground are actually connected to a supply rail
in single-supply systems. This is analogous to connecting a dual-supply input to the minus power
rail. This requirement for biasing the op amp inputs to achieve the desired output voltage
swings complicates single-supply designs.

When the signal source is not referenced to ground, shown below, the voltage difference between
ground and the reference voltage is amplified along with the signal. Unless the reference voltage
way inserted as a bias voltage, and such is not the case when the input signal is connected to
ground, the reference voltage must be stripped from the signal so that the op amp can provide
maximum dynamic range.










                SPLIT SUPPLY OPAMP CIRCUIT WITH REFERENCE VOLTAGE INPUT

An input bias voltage is used to eliminate the reference voltage when it must not appear in the
output voltage (shown below). The voltage Vref, is in both input circuits, hence it is named a 
COMMON-MODE VOLTAGE. Voltage feedback op amps reject common-mode voltages because their
input circuit is constructed with a differential amplifier (chosen because it has natural common-mode
voltage rejection capabilities).
















                SPLIT-SUPPLY OP AMP CIRCUIT WITH COMMON-MODE VOLTAGE

			"fontSize": 13.499274101921161,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "The integrated circuit OP AMP is the premier linear active device\nin present-day analog circuit applications. The device itself is a \ncomplex array of transistors, resistors and diodes, and capacitors,\nall fabricated and interconnected on a tiny silicon chip. In spite of \nits complexity, the device can be modeled by rather simple i-v char-\nteristics. We do not need to concern ourselves with what is going\non inside the package; rather, we treat the OP AMP using a behav-\nioural model that constraints the voltages and currents at the \nexternal terminals of the device.",

			"fontSize": 12.748412159752165,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "Certain matters of notation and nomenclature must be discussed \nbefore developing a circuit model for the OP AMP. The OP AMP is a \nfive terminal device, as shown in fig 1. The \"+\" and \"-\" symbols identify\nthe input terminals and are a short hand notation for the noninverting\nand inverting input terminals respectively. The other terminals are the \noutput and the positive and negative supply voltages usually labeled \n+Vcc and -Vcc. While some OP AMPs have more than five terminals,\nthese five are always present and are the only ones we will use in this\ntext. fig 2 shows a complete set of voltage and current variables for\nthe OP AMP. 			"text": "The voltage gain of an OP AMP is very large, usually greater than     . As\nlong as the net input(Vp - Vn) is very small, the output will be proportional to \nthe input. However, when A|Vp - Vn| > Vcc, the OP amp is saturated and the\noutput voltage is limited by the supply voltages.\n\n    The OP AMP has three modes of operatoins:\n1.  +Saturation mode when A(Vp - Vn) > Vcc and Vo = +Vcc.\n2.  -Saturation mode when A(Vp - Vn) < -Vcc and Vo = -Vcc.\n3. If Vo < -Vcc, then the\nassumption is wrong and the OP AMP is in the -saturation mode with Vo = -Vcc.\nIf Vo > +Vcc, then the assumption is wrong and the OP AMP is in the +saturation\nmode with Vo = +Vcc.",

			"fontSize": 10.504925234865423,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "    At first glance the element constraints of the ideal OP AMP appear to be fairly useless\nThey look more like connection constraints and are totally silent about the output quantities\n(vo and io), which are usually the signals of greatest interest. They seem to say that the\nOP AMP input terminals are simultaneously a short circuit (vp = vn) and an open circuit\n(ip = in = 0). In practice, however, the ideal model of the OP AMP is very useful because in\nlinear applications feedback is always present. That is, for the OP AMP to operate in a \nlinear mode, it is necessary for there to be feedback paths from the output to one or both\nof the inputs. These feedback paths ensure that         and make it possible for us to \nanalyze OP AMP circuits using the ideal OP AMP element constraints -----(ii).",

			"text": "The preceding analysis illustrates a general strategy for analyzing OP AMP circuits. We use \nnormal circuit analysis methods to express the OP AMP input voltages vp and vn in terms of circ-\nuit parameters. We then use the ideal OP AMP constraints vp = vn to solve for the overall circu-\nit input-output relationship\n    \n    The circuit in fig 5 is called a noninverting amplifier. The input-output relationship is of the \nform vo = Kvs, which reminds us that the circuit is linear. Fig 5b shows the functional block for \nthis circuit, where the proportionality constant k is:\n\n\n\n\nIn an OP AMP circuit the proportionality constant K is sometimes called the closed loop gain, \nbecause it defines the input-output relationship when the feedback loop is connected (closed).\n\n    When discussing OP AMP circuits, it is necessary to distinguish between two types of gains.\nThe first is the larger, OPEN-LOOP voltage gain provided by the OP AMP device itself. The \nsecond is the closed-loop voltage gain of the OP AMP circuit with a negative feedback path.\nNOTE: that equation vi indicates that the circuit gain is determined by the resistors in the \nfeedback path, not by the value of the OP AMP gain. In effect, feedback converts the OP AMP's\nvery large but variable gain into a much smaller but well defined gain.\n\n\n\n    Let us look at a first example of a noninverting OP AMP. consider the circuit shown in fig 6.\nLet us find the output voltage, the output current, the voltage gain, the output power and the\npower gain.\n    The circuit we just studied is contained within the shaded area. There is an input source, \nand an output source load. the gain of the OP AMP circuit is found using equation vi as:\n\n\n\nThe output voltage is found by substituting into equation v, but there is a possible complication.\nIn the derivation of equation v, the input was connected directly to the noninverting terminal. In\nthis circuit there is a 1k resistor between the source and the OP AMP. Doing KVL at the input\nyeilds:\n\nBut we recall that for an ideal OPAMP ip = in = 0. Therefore, there is no voltage drop across\nthe 1k resistor, so that the input voltage is impressed directly across the OPAMP. Equation v\nholds. The output voltage is found as:\n\n\nWe calculate the output current using Ohm's law as follows:\n\n\n\n\nThe output power is simply po = vo * io = 5 * 500^-6 = 2.5mW. It does not make sense to talk\nabout power gain with these types of circuits, since the input current ip is zero, the source does\nnot provide any power to the circuit. This would appear to say the circuit has infinite power gain.\nOf course, that is not true. There is a power source driving the OP AMP that is indeed providing\nthe necessary power to the load.\n\n\nREMARK: The problem of choosing resistance values in OP AMP circuit design problems deserves some\ndiscussion. Although values of resistances form a few ohms to several hundred mega ohms are comm-\nercially available, we generally limit ourselves to the range from about 1k to perhaps 10M. The lower \nlimit of 1k is imposed in part because of power dissipation in the resistors. Typically, we use resistors\nwith 1/4w power ratings or less. The maximum voltage in OP AMP circuits is often around 15V. The\nsmallest 1/4w resistance we can use is Rmin >= (15)^2/0.25 = 900 ohms, or about 1K. The upper\nbound of 1M comes about because surface leakages makes it difficult to maintain tolerance in a\nhigh-value resistor. High-value resistors are also noisy, which leads to problems when they are connec-\nted in the feedback path. The 1k to 1M range should be used as a guideline, not an inviolate deisgn\nrule. Actual design choices are influenced by system-specific factors and changes in technology.",

			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "OP AMP circuit analysis takes advantage of OP AMP building blocks that are connected in cascade\n(similar to series) to perform signal analysis functions that are too complex for any one building block\nalone. This approach greatly simplifies the analysis and design of these type of circuits. The reason \nthis works is that OP AMP building blocks, as we saw, have very low output resistance enabling other\ncircuits to be connected to their outputs without altering the function of either building block. In some\ncases, a passive circuit's signal processing function can be unintentionally altered by connecting that\ncircuit to another. When this effect occurs, the circuit is said to be \"LOADED\", and the effect needs\nto be considered. Some OP AMP building blocks, such as the noninverter just studied, also have very\nhigh input resistances. This feature enables them to be connected to the output of circuits that are\nsensitive to loading, such as voltage dividers, without affecting their signal processing function. In this\nsection, we introduce four more building blocks to complement the noninverter just studied, These are the\nvoltage follower, the inverting amplifier, the summer and the subractor. The key to using the building\nblock approach is to recognize the feedback pattern and to isolate the basic circuit as a building block.\nThe first example illustrates this process.\n\n\n\nEXAMPLE 2\nFind the input-output relationship, that is, the k of the circuit in fig 7.\n\nSOLUTION:\nAs we look at the circuit, we can recognize a voltage divider and a noninverting OP AMP-two separate\nbuilding blocks. Since the noninverter draws no current from the voltage divider, the output of the divider\nis unaltered and impressed on the input to the OP AMP at vp. Each block has its own gain: KVD for the\nvoltage divider and KAMP for the noninverter. That is, the output of the first building block becomes \nthe input of the second. We can find the gain of the voltage divider as follows:\n\n\n\nSince the noninverting amplifier has zero output resistance, the load RL has no effect on the output\nvoltage vo. Using equation v, the gain of the noninverting amplifier circuit is:\n\n\n\nThe overall circuit gain is found as:\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe gain Kcircuit is the product of KVD times KAMP because the amplifier circuit does not load the\nsource circuit since ip = 0",

			"fontSize": 10.671825120789391,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "The OP AMP in fig 8 is connected as a voltage follower or buffer. In this case, the feedback path is a\ndirect connection from the output to the inverting input. The feedback connection forces the condition \nvn = vo. The input current ip = 0, so there is no voltage across the source resistance Rs. Applying KVL,\nwe have the input condition vp = vs. The ideal OP AMP model requires vp = vn, so we conclude that \nvo = vs. By inspection, the closed-loop gain is K = 1. 			"text": "The circuit in fig 9 is called an inverting amplifier. The key feature of this circuit is that\nthe input signal and the feedback are both applied at the inverting input. Since the inverting\ninput. Since the noninverting input is grounded, we have vp = 0, an observation we will use\nshortly. The sum of currents entering node A can be written as:\n\n\n\n    The element constraints for the OP AMP are vp = vn and ip = in = 0. since vp = 0, it\nfollows that vn = 0. Substituting the OP AMP constraints into the above equation and \nsolving for the input-output relationship yeilds:\n\n\n\nThis result is of the form vo = Kvs where K is the closed loop gain. However, in this case\nthe voltage gain K = -R2/R1 is negative, indicating a signal inversion (Hence the name invert-\ning amplifier).\n\nREMARK: The inverting amplifier has a finite input resistance determined by the external \nresistor R1. This finite input resistance must be taken into account when analyzing circuits\nwith OP AMPs in the inverting amplifier configuration\n\n\nEXAMPLE:\n    Find the input-output relationship of the circuit in fig 10\n\nSOLUTION: The circuit to the right of node B is an inverting amplifier. The load resistance\nRL has no effect on the circuit transfer characteristics since the OP AMP has zero output\nresistance. However, the source circuit to the left of node B influenced by the input resista-\nnce of the inverting amplifier circuit. The effect can be seen by constructing a Thevenin\nequivalent of the circuit to the left of node B, as shown in figure 10b. By inspection of \n   figure 10a:\n\n\n\n\n\n\n in figure 10b, the Thevenin resistance is connected in series with the input resistor R3, \n   yielding the equivalent resistance Req = RT + R3, shown in figure 10c.\n \nThis circuit is in the form of an inverting amplifier, so we can write the input-output relatio-\nship relating vo and VT as:\n\n\nThe overall input-output relationship from the input source vs to the OP AMP output vo is\ndefined as follows:\n\n\n\n\n\nIt is important to note that the overall gain is not the product of the source circuit\nvoltage gain R2/(R1 + R2) and the inverting amplifier gain -R4/R3. In this circuit the two \nbuilding blocks interact because the input resistance of the inverting amplifier circuit loads\nthe source circuit.",

			"text": "The SUMMING AMPLIFIER OR ADDER or ADDER circuit is shown in figure 11. This circuit has two\ninputs connected at node A,which is called the SUMMING POINT. This configuration is similar to the inverting amplifier, so we\nstart by applying KCL to write the sum of currents entering the node A summing point.\n\n\n\nwith the noninverting input grounded, the OPAMP element constraints are vn=vp=0 and iN = 0, Subs-\ntituting these OP AMP constraints into the above equation, we can solve for the circuit input-out-\nput relationship:\n\n\n\n\nThe output is a weighted sum of the two inputs. The scale factors (or gains, as they are called)\nare determined by the ratio of the feedback resistor RF to the input resistor for each input; that\nis K1 = -RF/R1 and K2 = -RF/R2. 			"link": null,

			"fontSize": 16,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "There are many useful OP AMP circuits that are not simply interconnections of basic\nbuilding blocks. In such cases we use a modified form of node-voltage analysis that\nis based on the OP AMP connections shown below. The overall circuit contains N \nnodes, including the three associated with the OP AMP. Normally the objective is to \nfind the OP AMP output voltage vo relative to the reference node (ground). We\nassign node voltage variables at the OP AMP output. However, an ideal OP AMP \nacts like a dependent voltage source connected between the output terminal and\nground. As a result, the OP AMP output voltage is determined by the other node\nvoltages, and so we do not need to write a node equation at the OP AMP ouput\nnode.\n    We formulate node equations at the other N-2 nonreference nodes in the usual\nway. Since there are N-1 node voltages, we seem to have unknowns than the equati-\nns. However, the OP AMP forces the condition vp = vn. This eliminates one unknown\nnode voltage since these two nodes are forced to have identical voltages. Finally,\nremember that the ideal OP AMP draws no current at its inputs (ip=in=0), so these\ncurrents can be ignored when formulating node equations.\n    The following steps outline an approach to the formulation of node equations\nfor OP AMP circuits:\n\nSTEP 1:  Identify a node voltage at all nonreference nodes, including OP AMP outp-\n        uts, but do not formulate node equations at the OP AMP output nodes.\nSTEP 2: Formulate node equations at the remaining nonreference nodes and then\n        use the ideal OP AMP voltage constraints vp=vn to reduce the number of\n        unknowns.",

Since there are N-1 node voltages, we seem to have unknowns than the equati-\nns. However, the OP AMP forces the condition vp = vn. This eliminates one unknown\nnode voltage since these two nodes are forced to have identical voltages. Finally,\nremember that the ideal OP AMP draws no current at its inputs (ip=in=0), so these\ncurrents can be ignored when formulating node equations.\n    The following steps outline an approach to the formulation of node equations\nfor OP AMP circuits:\n\nSTEP 1:  Identify a node voltage at all nonreference nodes, including OP AMP outp-\n        uts, but do not formulate node equations at the OP AMP output nodes.\nSTEP 2: Formulate node equations at the remaining nonreference nodes and then\n        use the ideal OP AMP voltage constraints vp=vn to reduce the number of\n        unknowns.",

			"fontSize": 16,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "When complex networks are put into the feedback, the circuits get harder to analyze\nbecause the simple gain equations cannot be used. The usual technique is to write and\nnode or loop equations. There is only one input voltage, so superposition is not of any\nuse. but Thevenin's theorem can be used as is shown in the sample problem below.\n\nSometimes it is desirable to have a low resistance path to ground in the feedback loop.\nStandard inverting op amps can not do this when the driving circuit sets the input resistor\nvalue, and the gain specification sets the feedback resistor value. Inserting a T network\nin the feedback loop, yields a degree of freedom that enables both specification to be met\nwith a low dc resistance path in the feedback loop.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nBreak the circuit at point X-Y, stand on the terminals looking into R4, and calculate the\nThevenin equivalent voltage as shown below. The Thevenin equivalent impedance is also\ncalculated\n\n\n\n\n\nReplace the output circuit with the Thevenin equivalent circuit as shown below, and calculate\nthe gain with the aid of the inverting gain equation as shown below:\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n                    Thevenin's Theorem Applied to T Network\nSubstituting the Thevenin equivalents into the previous equations yeilds:\n\n\n\nSpecifications for the circuit you are required to build are an inverting amplifier with\nan input resistance of 10K (RG = 10K), a gain of 100, and a feedback resistance of\n20K or less, The inverting amplifier op amp circuit cannot meet these specifications\nbecuase RF must equal 1000K. Inserting a T network with \n                            R2=R4=10K and R3=485K\napproximately meets the specifications.",
			"rawText": "When complex networks are put into the feedback, the circuits get harder to analyze\nbecause the simple gain equations cannot be used. The usual technique is to write and\nnode or loop equations. Inserting a T network\nin the feedback loop, yields a degree of freedom that enables both specification to be met\nwith a low dc resistance path in the feedback loop.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nBreak the circuit at point X-Y, stand on the terminals looking into R4, and calculate the\nThevenin equivalent voltage as shown below. 			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "We have previously assumed that all op amps were powered from dual or split supplies and\nthis is not the case in today's world of portable, battery-powered equipment. Any input sources\nconnected to ground are automatically referenced to the center of the supply voltage, so\nthe output voltage is automatically referenced to ground.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n                            SPLIT-SUPPLY OP AMP CIRCUIT\n\nSingle-supply systems do not have the convenient ground reference that dual-supply systems\nhave, thus biasing must be employed to ensure that the output voltage swings between the\ncorrect voltages. Input sources connected to ground are actually connected to a supply rail\nin single-supply systems. This is analogous to connecting a dual-supply input to the minus power\nrail.
